        "title": "Checking for Jakarta Validation annotation during compilation in Eclipse",
        "body": "<p>If I declare a method that uses a validation annotation on its parameter, for instance:<\/p>\n<pre><code>public void myMethod(@NonNull String s){}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n<p>I would like Eclipse to mark<\/p>\n<pre><code>myMethod(null);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n<p>as a compilation error.<\/p>\n<p>Is it doable ? (After comment it seems there's a specific configuration in Eclipse for null checking, but what about the others ?)<\/p>\n<p>I added dependencies to org.hibernate.validator:hibernate-validator and jakarta.validation:jakarta.validation-api.<\/p>\n<p>I enabled Annotation Processing (had to add specific configuration on the project, I did not find the option for Java Compiler at the Workspace level)\nI added both jars in the Factory Path of the annotation processor<\/p>\n<p>Still nothing happens.\nAm I missing something ? Is it even possible ?<\/p>\n<p>Or should these be considered just declarative, (and in this case do I even need to import the hibernate-validator implementation ?)<\/p>\n",
