        "creation_date": 1704881481,
        "body": "<p>It seems the API is not meant for that. However Eclipse can naturally handle some annotations related to null values.<\/p>\n<p>There is no general preferences for this but annotation handling can be set at the project level.\nProject &gt; Properties &gt; Java Compiler &gt; Annotations Processing\nEnable project specific settings\nEnable annotation processing<\/p>\n<p>The severity level needs to be set, this one can be done at General level instead of project.\nPreferences &gt; Compiler &gt; Errors/Warning\nIn the &quot;Null analysis&quot; section check &quot;Enable annotation-based null analysis&quot;\nThe &quot;Use default annotations for null specifications&quot; has a &quot;Configure&quot; button.<\/p>\n<p>Here are the handled annotations: @Nullable @NonNull @NonNullByDefault. These are Eclipse annotation but you can add other annotations to be handled for the same meaning.<\/p>\n<p>However, this is the only available, there is no specific configuration that would configure the use of @Positive or other jakarta annotations.\nYou then need to define<\/p>\n<p>Within the Annotations Processing section, there is Factory Path subsection to define other annotation processor than the default one, but adding hibernate validator here had no effect for me. Probably because there is no configuration available to set a severity on these annotation violations.<\/p>\n<p>Note: Having an error severity level on a @NonNull annotation would prevent tests (that would assertThrow an exception for instance) from compiling.<\/p>\n",
